For you religious types--do you think that this cloned baby has a soul? If not, why?<br>
Again, I don't believe in souls, but at this other board, I'm debating the logic of it. <br>
Anyone care to have a go around with it?<br>
Emmy <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;I'm a goddamned marvel of modern science!!&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ctrlaltdelirious>CtrlAltDelirious</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#3333ff>(12/28/02 2:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.liquid2k.com/cordelia/images/heartsandstars.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: So, all this cloning business...</span><hr size=1> I'm not a religious type, but it is an interesting question - especially when you consider the ramifications if this child (if it is in fact a clone) turns out to be a normal, happy, person who can choose between right and wrong - and not the devil spawn (think Damien in the Omen) that some would have us believe that it will be.<br>
<br>
I think when we are born there is a 'life force' - call it chi, a soul, consciousness - that exists separately but intrinsicly a part of us.  It is this that makes us, well... 'us'.  Do I think that this is g-dgiven - no.  Do I think that even a cloned child can have one - yes.<br>
<br>
When artificial insemination was a new and burgeoning science the same questions were there, and decades later we see that it was just silly.<br>
<br>
I have reservations about the cloning process, and I think this group, if they have succeeded, has just put a major roadblock in the research into therapeutic cloning.  Because of their beliefs (that is a whole other subject), and that cloning is a major part of it, the backlash will outlaw all types of cloning.<br>
<br>
TheCAD <p>&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Do not meddle in the affairs of dragons, because you are crunchy and taste good with ketchup.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt; </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#3333ff>(12/28/02 2:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Great question Em</span><hr size=1> Cloning is a fact whether or not this latest Clonaid claim is true. It will happen because it can and I just wish we had more public debate about how it will/should/could be. All these attempts to stop or ignore it in this country are thwarting any effort to get a grasp on what this means and start to develop dialoge for guidelines, national and international laws for cloning and the clones themselves, ethical standards and practices etc. and I would imagine the discussion of whether or not clones have a soul would be a very large part of that.<br>
<br>
I don't personally believe we have souls either and I don't think it matters. If parts of tissue are cloned (like a nose or ear) that should be separate from the cloning of a baby. A cloned baby would have the same rights any of us do and it's own personality and identity. I think too many of the opponents of this are hung up on a &quot;Boys From Brazil&quot; scenario. <br>
<br>
I would be very interested though in the perspective of religious folks. One would think a cloned baby would get a soul just like any new little fetus from the whatever deity oversees this--or if not would we have some sort of freakish zombie like pod people roaming around? <br>
<br>
I have a hypothetical too. For anyone who asserts cloned babies have no souls, would abortion then be acceptable for this mother? Would she still be committing murder if the baby were a clone?<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dynamohumm6>dynamohumm6</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.pro-rock.com/ikonboard/avatars/clutch-elephant1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Rocket Queen</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#3333ff>(12/28/02 7:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.clipartconnection.com/img/6/WB/zed_non_com/clipconxn/animations/science/0563.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Great question Em</span><hr size=1> Well, the thing that gets me about this is that so many of the folks that are so &quot;anti-clone&quot; seem to think that a clone is an exact replica of another human being. A clone is an exact<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>DNA match</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of another human, but you also have to take into consideration the &quot;nurture&quot; side of the &quot;nurture vs. nature&quot; issue. <br>
For example, a clone of Mozart would look like Mozart, sound like Mozart, and have many of the same predispositions as Mozart, but the clone's personality would not be exactly the same. Know what I'm saying? Identical twins are exact DNA replicas of each other, but they each have their own separate and distinct personalities. <br>
Anyway, just wanted to throw that in there.<br>
Em <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;I'm a goddamned marvel of modern science!!&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#3333ff>(12/28/02 8:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Cloning Laws</span><hr size=1> ITA emmy and this misunderstanding (not unlike stem cell research) is at the root of a great deal of the right wing hubbub over this. I even saw a guy on some news show the other night saying the Bush admin will enforce laws against cloning by not allowing a couple that went out of the country to have a child this way re-enter with the child!! How could this ultimately be enforceable and what are the implications for the rights of the children?<br>
<br>
Like I said too--would these same folks be okay with aborting cloned fetuses or are they willing to make them second class citizens??? Weird. We better get a grip on this soon though so we can have a place at the table for the discussions...after all don't we handle sperm donations and inseminations despite all the initial concerns that there would be brothers and sisters unknowingly getting married (same donor), all these weird diseases popping up and fathers coming back for their babies?? Good grief! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ctrlaltdelirious>CtrlAltDelirious</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#3333ff>(12/29/02 12:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.liquid2k.com/cordelia/images/heartsandstars.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Great question Em</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Identical twins are exact DNA replicas of each other, but they each have their own separate and distinct personalities.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And unique fingerprints!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>you also have to take into consideration the &quot;nurture&quot; side of the &quot;nurture vs. nature&quot; issue<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I actually was thinking about that last night.  This really will provide a fascinating twist to that debate - unlike identical twins who generally are raised in the same environment, clones would be raised in completely different situations.<br>
<br>
And Mama G, you're right.  Misunderstanding is the root of a lot of the misinformation put forth by people, and I think many of them are not separating their personal beliefs from the issue.  Christopher Reeve had it right on Donahue the other night - religion has no place in this debate.<br>
<br>
He too brought up the issue that if he went to another country to have any form of treatment, under the law that is coming before the senate, he could be arrested and put in jail upon his arrival back in the United States.<br>
