<br>
A male cannot truly be cloned. He has no provision of host cells. A woman, by producing an ovum, does. There is more to a cell than just the genetic material in the nucleus, there is also all the genetic material in the extra-nucleic fluids. RNA that run the cell internally. So a macroscopic clone still isn't a clone on a microscopic level. Furthermore, we don't know how much the RNA contributes to the development of a person, Nature v. Nurture aside. So there is a whole array of possible differences between the older and younger twins/clones. Identical twins are actually mirrors of each other, reflections. The hair curls in opposite directions, that sort of thing. A clone would be truly identical in that it curled in the same direction. Does this have to do with the direction of the genetic duplication during cellular division at the time the twins egg split? We Don't Know!<br>
